\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
Marginal Medalists
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space \qquad{}
\end_inset

Marginal medalists and non-medalists have similar career trajectories in
 terms of Olympic results.
 Despite missing out on a debut medal, 4th place finishers perform no worse
 than 3rd place finishers in subsequent Olympic Games.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There are several ways to interpret this finding.
 If marginal medalists are typically higher in ability compared to marginal
 non-medalists, then winning a medal may have a predominantly negative impact.
 As mentioned in the introduction, gold medalists and champion athletes
 in various sports have been documented to face greater difficulty preparing
 for and performing during future competitions 
